Qt unit testing-basic usage

Transfer from:http://blog.csdn.net/yizhou2010/article/details/78272505

Frame generation

QtTestLibThe framework provides a simple and easy-to-use unit test framework. First, we automatically create a test framework through Qt Creator. To

Create a project named MyTest

Select QtGui and QtWidget (selected according to the needs of the test project)

Class name: MyTest, slot function testQString, type select "performance test" (macro QBENCHMARK will be automatically added), and check "use test database", "QApplication required",
 
-Use test data set: The test data set slot function will be automatically added, namely testQString_data
-Need QApplication: If checked, the macro QTEST_MAIN will be called automatically; if not checked, the macro QTEST_APPLESS_MAIN will be called automatically; both are implementedmian()Function, but the latter will not instantiate the QApplication object;
-Generate initialization and cleanup code: If checked, it will be added automaticallyinitTestCase()withcleanupTestCase()function;

Then it is selected by default, so Qt Creator will automatically generate a test template for us. We can see that the test template defines a test class MyTest inherited from QObject, includingvoid testQString_data()withvoid testQString()Two slot functions, the macro QTEST_MAIN, and#include "tst_mytest.moc"(This is because our class declaration and implementation are in the same .cpp file, so the .moc file must be included). In addition, when we open the .pro file in the project, we can find that it has been addedQT += testlib。

Let's add the content that needs to be tested.

Test of function toUpper() in QString class

1. Add the data to be tested in the test data set

  1. void MyTest::testQString_data()
  2. {
  3.     QTest::addColumn<QString>("string");
  4.     QTest::addColumn<QString>("result");
  5.     QTest::newRow("lower") << "hello"<<"HELLO";
  6.     QTest::newRow("mix")<<"HellO"<<"HELLO";
  7.     QTest::newRow("upper")<<"HELLO"<<"HELLO";
  8. }

We passedaddColumn()The function defines two element columns of type QString, named string and result respectively. Also passnewRow()The function adds three test data sets, named lower, mix, and upper. From this, we can get a test data table:

Serial number name string(QString) result (QString class)
0 lower “hello” “HELLO”
1 mix “HellO” “HELLO”
2 Upper “HELLO” “HELLO”

2. Add the function to be tested in the test slot function

  1. void MyTest::testQString()
  2. {
  3.     QFETCH(QString, string);
  4.     QFETCH(QString, result);
  5.     QCOMPARE(string.toUpper(), result);
  6.     QBENCHMARK {
  7.         string.toUpper();
  8.     }
  9. }
  • 1
  • 2

  • 8
  • 9

We obtain the test data in the test data table through the macro QFETCH, the first parameter is the type of the element column, the second parameter is the element column name (consistent with the definition in the data table), and the macro QCOMPARE is used to compare the function execution return Whether the value of is consistent with the expected value. In addition, the performance of the function is tested through the macro QBENCHMARK, which will call the function multiple times to make more accurate measurements.

Build and run the program, we can get the following output:

  1. ********* Start testing of MyTest *********
  2. Config: Using QtTest library 5.9.1, Qt 5.9.1 (i386-little_endian-ilp32 shared (dynamic) debug build; by MSVC 2015)
  3. PASS   : MyTest::initTestCase()
  4. PASS   : MyTest::testQString(lower)
  5. RESULT : MyTest::testQString():"lower": 0.0015 msecs per iteration (total: 51, iterations: 32768)

GUI event test

First, we add two slot functions to the test class MyTesttestGui_data()withtestGui()To test the event response in QLineEdit. To
1. Add test data set

  1. void MyTest::testGui_data()
  2. {
  3.     QTest::addColumn<QTestEventList>("event");
  4.     QTest::addColumn<QString>("result");
  5.  
  6.     QTestEventList list1;
  7.     list1.addKeyClicks("hello world");
  8.     QTest::newRow("item 0 ")<<list1<<QString("hello world");
  9.  
  10.     QTestEventList list2;
  11.     list2.addKeyClicks("abs0");
  12.     list2.addKeyClick(Qt::Key_Backspace);
  13.     QTest::newRow("item 1")<<list2<<QString("abs");    
  14. }

Similarly, we defined a QTestEventList type named event and a QStirng type named result through the addColumn() function, and added two test data sets through the newRow() function.

2. Event test implementation

  1. void MyTest::testGui()
  2. {
  3.     QFETCH(QTestEventList, event);
  4.     QFETCH(QString, result);
  5.  
  6.     QLineEdit lineEdit;
  7.     event.simulate(&lineEdit);
  8.     QCOMPARE(lineEdit.text(), result);
  9. }

byQTestEventList::simulate()To simulate the events in the list, use the macro QFETCH to load test data, and use the macro QCOMPARE to compare.

Build and run the program, you can find in the test output information:

  1. PASS   : MyTest::testGui(item 0 )
  2. PASS   : MyTest::testGui(item 1)

Qt Test command line parameters

During the test, what information we need to output, whether to output to a file, test options, performance test options, etc. can be configured through the Qt Test command line parameters. The specific syntax is as follows:

testname [options] [testfunctions[:testdata]]...
  • 1

All options and parameters can be explained on the official websitehttp://doc.qt.io/qt-5/qtest-overview.html, The following are two commonly used options:
-o filename.format (formats include: txt, xml, csv...): output test information to a specified file in a specified format;
-silent: only output error information;

The method of configuring command line parameter options in Qt Creator: Configure related options in "Project" -> "Run" -> "Command line arguments". To
